## 3. Technology Stack & Why

### Spring Boot 4.0.1

```
WHY:
  Latest Spring Boot with Spring Framework 7.x
  Jakarta EE 11 namespace (jakarta.* not javax.*)
  Better performance with virtual threads
  Native compilation support
  Spring MVC + Spring Data JPA out of the box
```

### Drools 8.44.0.Final

```
WHY:
  Rule-based engine — discount logic lives in DRL files
  DRL files compiled at runtime from DB — no redeployment
  Salience (priority) controls rule execution order
  no-loop prevents same rule firing twice in one session
  KieContainer holds compiled rules (singleton, thread-safe)
  KieSession executes rules (new per request, disposed after)

KEY CONCEPTS:
  KieServices    → factory to build everything Drools needs
  KieFileSystem  → in-memory file system to hold DRL content
  KieBuilder     → compiles DRL into bytecode
  KieContainer   → holds compiled KieBase (reloaded on change)
  KieSession     → stateful working memory per cart request
  insert()       → puts Cart and DiscountResult into session
  fireAllRules() → executes all matching rules
  dispose()      → releases session memory (MUST be called)
```

### Jackson 3.x (tools.jackson)

```
WHY Spring Boot 4.x uses Jackson 3.x:
  New package: tools.jackson (not com.fasterxml.jackson)
  JavaTimeModule is BUILT INTO jackson-databind 3.x
  No separate dependency needed
  Builder pattern replaces direct mapper.configure()

CRITICAL CHANGES from Jackson 2.x to 3.x:
  ObjectMapper    → tools.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper
  JsonMapper      → tools.jackson.databind.json.JsonMapper
  DateTimeFeature → tools.jackson.databind.cfg.DateTimeFeature
  Configuration   → JsonMapper.builder().configure(...).build()
```

### H2 (Development) / MySQL (Production)

```
WHY H2 for dev:
  In-memory database — no setup required
  Auto schema creation from JPA entities
  H2 console at /h2-console for debugging

WHY MySQL for prod:
  Persistent storage
  Production-grade performance
  Switch via application-prod.properties
```

